metadata.name: one hour #210
metadata.description:
`one hour` is an interactive installation exploring the bond between humans and computers, inviting you to pause and share a meditative moment with an algorithmic stranger.

Rather than conventionally interacting with the piece, lower your guard and allow it to interact with you through an intimately human connection - a heart beat. `one hour` follows this heart as it beats through an hour of its enduring existence, captured by an EKG divided into 60 rows of 60 seconds each. Stylistically, it emulates realistic paper and ink using custom texture and line renderers. The piece will play through the duration of the hour, pause for five minutes, then begin anew.

`one hour` was created for a physical installation, projected to a wall and animated in real time. By default it will render at high speed to reveal the preview. For the most immersive experience at home, it should be viewed in full screen and adjusted to real time speed (controlled via the number keys).

||| controls

[s] save as png
[r] reset animation
[l] toggle looping [default on]
[1-5] adjust render speed
[--1] real time (1 hour) [recommended]
[--2] 6x (10 minutes)
[--3] 60x (1 minute)
[--4] 300x (12 seconds) [default]
[--5] full speed

metadata.name: Decadence #469
metadata.description:
Decadence should not be misunderstood. Over time, the word has had various meanings (political and cultural) but has also been associated with Symbolism and Aestheticism.

The contemporary definition of decadence emerged in the late 19th century and praised artifice over nature, sophistication over simplicity, at the same time defying contemporary discourse of decline by embracing subjects and styles that critics considered over-refined. 

Nowadays, decadence also refers to stagnation and intellectual exhaustion at a high level of material prosperity and technological development which leads to an excessive indulgence in pleasure or luxury.

In this context, Decadence is a reflection on the collaboration between Jerome Herr and David Mrugala (thedotisblack). A collaboration that started several months ago with a simple grid of random values, that soon became an experiment of creativity, always in the search of expectations, interest in excessive indulgence of visual pleasure, a fascination with the bizarre, all packaged in a series of generative images with an aesthetics that values excess ‚Äì That is Decadence.

- press 's' to save a standard image
- press 'h' to save a high resolution image

Jerome Herr

Jerome Herr is from Luxembourg. Since 2015 he has created generative art with a passion for design and visual explorations. He is an active member of the creative coding community and a successful NFT artist, both on Teia and Fxhash.

David Mrugala

David is a German architect and intermedia artist, who lives in South Korea. He is the founder of thedotisblack, a platform and an archive for research design on (generative) drawings and animations made with code.

metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #252
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Elasticity #122
metadata.description:
Elasticity is a collection that explores the ambiguity of discrete continuity in architecture.

Elasticity is a tectonic, generative system that combines simple, discrete parts into an elastic relationship between part and whole, creating a discrete and continuous elastic form. A form that celebrates the continuity of digital variation while respecting a discrete approach to a digital whole.

It is a generative follow-up to the project CM.CollabWood, where the same parts were embedded in a real-time participatory architectural environment, where clusters of parts were placed by participants in real-time in collective design sessions to create tangible collective open forms.

___________________________________________________
Controls:
‚Ä¢ 'P' pause/play animation
‚Ä¢ 'B' monochrome mode (wait a bit for recalculation)

Resize Canvas in live/open mode:
(press once and wait for recalculation!)
‚Ä¢ 'DoubleClick' go Fullscreen
‚Ä¢ '1' square 1024x1024
‚Ä¢ '2' square 2048x2048
‚Ä¢ '3' square 3072x3072
‚Ä¢ '4' square 4096x4096 (might not work on all laptops)
‚Ä¢ '5' landscape 4000x3000
‚Ä¢ '6' portrait 3000x4000
‚Ä¢ '7' fullHD 1920x1080
‚Ä¢ '8' UHD 3840 x 2160
‚Ä¢ '9' square small(for sharing a gif on twitter) 512x512
‚Ä¢ '0' flex. adapt to current window size

Save & Export in live/open mode:
‚Ä¢ 's' save a .png of in current resolution
‚Ä¢ 'g' save a seamless loop .gif in current resolution
(press the key and wait for export, might take some time, consider with higher resolutions files get pretty big)

Steps to save a gif/png :
‚Ä¢ go in live/open mode (wait)
‚Ä¢ resize canvas to your desired resolution (wait)
‚Ä¢ press s or g and wait for recalculation & download to finish
‚Ä¢ enjoy elasticity :)
___________________________________________________


This token may not work on mobile(!), but it allows exporting .png and .gif (see controls) to enjoy elasticity on different displays or mobile. Tested on Mozilla, Chrome, Safari. Created with P5js & p5.createLoop

Elasticity Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2022

metadata.name: A24Z #451
metadata.description:
Every artist and collector feels the joy of both creating and collecting. But if I could share the joy of creating with collectors. And collectors with their family and friends, what may be an additive process of joy is now perhaps exponential. Joy to the power of 26 to be exact. 

In this work I invite my friends and collectors to collaborate with me. Though not in coding, but together in a process of creating narratives and visuals. Code and story. We didn‚Äôt use github, just a simple p5.js editor to try out different programs and palettes. Pedrofe and J0rdan pick their palettes tastefully and carefully. okeoke, perhaps more of a genius than he lets on, picks his palettes blind. No hex color picker. Just straight up rhymes.  

In our discussions verbal language was forbidden. Only emojis were allowed to express our tastes and views. Each emojis put down on google doc was taken with absolutely seriousness. 

Pedro: Loves to taking his daily walks on ‚ÄúMagic Mushroom Mountain‚Äù

J0rdan: Wonders about ‚ÄúQuark Question Quiches‚Äù

Okeoke: Just get lost in ‚ÄúFinnegans‚Äô Flower Fields.‚Äù

It has been a great joy to present our illustration book A24Z, 8 more than you know who. Each page expresses the alphabet with the best of our knowledge in semantics and sarcasm. Collect just 1 page, collect the alphabets that spell out your name, collect the whole A to Z. Read it to your children or loved ones. Though you might need to interpolate or extrapolate with great imagination which children all have. But most importantly, like all children, have fun!

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. Preview images are compressed or broken, test capture at 300 sec.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Crude Acceptance #145
metadata.description:
It was there when we arrived
    No owners, no gatekeepers
    The opportunity to explore
    The chance to transform
    What we are
    What we see
    And a trace will came with us
    And that way it will multiply
    As long as we allow
    To leave here a part of us
    It will be there when we leave
    No owners, no gatekeepers
    But itself



  Controls
  Format:
  'f' - switch square/full screen format

  View:

  'Arrow Up/Down' - Decrease/Increase distance to origin
  'Mouse Drag' - View Rotation


  Export:
  'x' - show/hide export menu
  'm' - quick canvas save
